# Documentation style

Write for a skilled developer who is new to Li — not for a thesis committee.

## Voice

- Use **complete sentences** and plain language; avoid telegraphic bullet chains
- Explain **why** before **how** when introducing a design choice
- Prefer short sections with clear headings over one long wall of text
- Use tables and diagrams when they reduce ambiguity (pipelines, type lists, phases)

## Structure (every major doc)

1. One-sentence **what this page is for**
2. **Prerequisites** or links to prior reading
3. **Content** with runnable examples where possible
4. **Related links** at the end

## Code in docs

- Show full, copy-pasteable commands (no `...` omissions in shell blocks)
- Label language on fenced blocks: ` ```nim ` for Li surface syntax
- Pair “good” examples with one “fails at compile time” example when teaching types

## Naming

- Follow [philosophy.md](../../docs/language/philosophy.md) — domain words, snake_case procs, readable imports
- Say **Li** (the language) and **lic** (the compiler)
- Link to canonical spec sections instead of duplicating large tables
- Date major spec revisions; mark **Status:** Planning | Active | Deprecated

## Anti-patterns

- Walls of identifiers without prose
- Duplicating the full numeric/data-structure roadmaps — link to the design spec
- Promising timelines without pointing to the master plan phase map
